04918nam a22007455i 9780801459436DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014594367 a10.7591/97808014594362doi  a(DE-B1597)503371  a(OCoLC)1059270924  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD7368.K86bZ43 2010eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.5/50951352221 aZhang, Li, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Search of Paradise :bMiddle-Class Living in a Chinese Metropolis /cLi Zhang. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b15 halftones, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Farewell to Welfare Housing -- t2. Unlocking the Real Estate Machine -- t3. Emerging Landscapes of Living -- t4. Spatializing Class -- t5. Accumulation by Displacement -- t6. Recasting Self-Worth -- t7. Privatizing Community Governing and Its Limits -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new revolution in homeownership and living has been sweeping the booming cities of China. This time the main actors on the social stage are not peasants, migrants, or working-class proletariats but middle-class professionals and entrepreneurs in search of a private paradise in a society now dominated by consumerism. No longer seeking happiness and fulfillment through collective sacrifice and socialist ideals, they hope to find material comfort and social distinction in newly constructed gated communities. This quest for the good life is profoundly transforming the physical and social landscapes of urban China.Li Zhang, who is from Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, turns a keen ethnographic eye on her hometown. She combines her analysis of larger political and social issues with fine-grained details about the profound spatial, cultural, and political effects of the shift in the way Chinese urban residents live their lives and think about themselves. In Search of Paradise is a deeply informed account of how the rise of private homeownership is reconfiguring urban space, class subjects, gender selfhood, and ways of life in the reform era.New, seemingly individualistic lifestyles mark a dramatic move away from yearning for a social utopia under Maoist socialism. Yet the privatization of property and urban living have engendered a simultaneous movement of public engagement among homeowners as they confront the encroaching power of the developers. This double movement of privatized living and public sphere activism, Zhang finds, is a distinctive feature of the cultural politics of the middle classes in contemporary China. Theoretically sophisticated and highly accessible, Zhang's account will appeal not only to those interested in China but also to anyone interested in spatial politics, middle-class culture, and postsocialist governing in a globalizing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHousingzChinazKunming Shi. 0aMiddle classzChinazKunming Shi. 0aPrivatizationzChinazKunming Shi. 0aReal estate businesszChinazKunming Shi. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145943640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801459436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801459436.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_